.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis first comprehensive study of Norwegian humanities education employs systems theory to analyze its transformation from a form of teacher training to its modern status as research-oriented generalist education.Using historical documents and statistical analyses, Vidar Grotta shows that the expansion of the post-war research system in Norway led to an increase in admissions to humanities education in the 1960s and an ensuing research drift in humanities curricula. Interacting with certain political dynamics and the knowledge economy that has emerged since the 1970s, this research drift resulted in a shift in humanists' career patterns and a transformation of the societal functions of the humanities.  afunded by Department of Education at the University of Oslo  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEducationxResearch. 0aEducation. 0aHumanitiesxStudy and teaching (Higher)zNorwayxHistoryy20th century. 0aHumanitieszNorwayxHistoryy20th century. 0aNiklas Luhmann. 0aSociology. 4aEducation. 4aEducational Research. 4aHigher Education. 4aNiklas Luhmann. 4aNorway. 4aScience. 4aSociology of Education. 4aSociology of Science. 4aSociology. 4aSystems Theory. 4aUniversity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aEducation.  aEducational Research.  aHigher Education.  aNiklas Luhmann.  aNorway.  aScience.  aSociology of Education.  aSociology of Science.  aSociology.  aSystems Theory.  aUniversity.2 aDepartment of Education at the University of Osloefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2019z978311071956708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz97831106107